('business:4-4-consumer-law:misc:0db124f9', 'business', 'business:4-4-consumer-law', '4.4 Consumer Law', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Repeating earlier analysis points in a conclusion will earn evaluation marks in a 7-mark question.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Repeating earlier points in a conclusion earns zero evaluation marks. A good conclusion makes a new, justified judgement using specific context from the case study — using ''It depends on...'' or ''However, this is only the case if...'' style reasoning to show higher-level thinking.</p>", "question": "What happens if a student simply repeats earlier analysis points in a 7-mark conclusion?", "options": ["They earn 1 mark for effort", "They earn zero evaluation marks", "They earn full evaluation marks for consistency", "They earn analysis marks retroactively"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Repeating earlier points in a conclusion earns zero evaluation marks — a good conclusion must make a new, justified judgement."}'::jsonb),
('business:4-4-consumer-law:tips:4a960d9c', 'business', 'business:4-4-consumer-law', '4.4 Consumer Law', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Identify / State — 1 mark — One Point. Full Stop. Move On.", "reading": "\n          <p>A 1-mark <strong>''Identify'' or ''State''</strong> question needs exactly one correct, specific point. No explanation. No examples. No paragraphs — just one precise, accurate statement.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>The Formula:</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li>One clear, specific point = 1 mark ✅</li>\n            <li>A vague or general point = 0 marks ❌</li>\n          </ul>\n    \n          <p><strong>❌ Bad Answer (0 marks):</strong><br/>\n          <em>\"Consumer law protects customers.\"</em><br/>\n          Too vague — it doesn''t identify any specific protection.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>✅ Good Answer (1 mark):</strong><br/>\n          <em>\"Goods must be of satisfactory quality.\"</em><br/>\n          Specific, accurate, and directly answers the question.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>⚠️ Critical Examiner Warning:</strong> Many students confuse consumer law with employment law, writing about fair wages or working conditions. This scores ZERO — no matter how detailed the answer is. The mark scheme explicitly states: \"No further marks can be gained without understanding\" of what consumer law actually requires.</p>\n        ", "question": "Why does ''Consumer law protects customers'' score 0 marks as an answer to a 1-mark identify question?", "options": ["It is factually incorrect about consumer rights", "It wrongly confuses consumer law with employment law", "It is too long for a 1-mark question", "It is too vague to identify a specific protection"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card explains this answer is too vague — it doesn''t identify any specific protection required under consumer law."}'::jsonb),
('business:4-4-consumer-law:tips:14fa8514', 'business', 'business:4-4-consumer-law', '4.4 Consumer Law', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Explain — 2 marks — Identify It, Then Apply It to the Business", "reading": "\n          <p>A 2-mark <strong>''Explain''</strong> question requires you to name an impact of consumer law AND link it specifically to the business named in the question. Two clear steps — one per mark.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>The 2-Step Formula:</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><strong>Step 1 — Identify the impact (1 mark):</strong> Name a specific way consumer law affects businesses.</li>\n            <li><strong>Step 2 — Apply to the specific business (1 mark):</strong> Use a detail from the case study to show how this applies to that particular business.</li>\n          </ul>\n    \n          <p><strong>❌ Bad Answer (1 mark max):</strong><br/>\n          <em>\"Consumer law could affect Tesco''s reputation.\"</em><br/>\n          Identifies an impact but does not apply it to Tesco specifically using case study detail.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>✅ Good Answer (2 marks):</strong><br/>\n          <em>\"If Tesco plc sells products which are not as described (K — 1 mark), it could receive poor press coverage leading to a loss of sales (APP — 1 mark applied to Tesco as a major UK retailer).\"</em></p>\n    \n          <p><strong>🚫 Knowledge Dumping Alert:</strong> You only need ONE impact, explained and applied to the business. Writing everything you know about consumer law will NOT earn more marks — only one applied point is needed.</p>\n        ", "question": "What are the two steps required to earn full marks on a 2-mark ''Explain'' question?", "options": ["State three separate requirements of consumer law", "Identify an impact, then apply it to the business", "Identify an impact and then evaluate its importance", "Give two direct quotes from the case study"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The 2-step formula is: Step 1 identify a specific impact, Step 2 apply it to the named business using case study detail."}'::jsonb),
('business:4-4-consumer-law:tips:1b39e9f4', 'business', 'business:4-4-consumer-law', '4.4 Consumer Law', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Analyse — 3 marks — The Holy Trinity: U → APP → AN", "reading": "\n          <p>A 3-mark <strong>''Analyse''</strong> question is the most common extended question on consumer law. You must follow a strict 3-step structure — missing any one step costs you marks. And without demonstrating understanding of consumer law first, you cannot earn ANY further marks.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>The 3-Step Formula:</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><strong>Step 1 — Understanding (U — 1 mark):</strong> State a specific requirement of consumer law: \"Consumer law requires goods to be of satisfactory quality / fit for purpose / as described.\"</li>\n            <li><strong>Step 2 — Application (APP — 1 mark):</strong> Link directly to the specific business in the case study using a quoted or paraphrased detail from the text.</li>\n            <li><strong>Step 3 — Analysis (AN — 1 mark):</strong> State the financial or operational impact: costs, profit, reputation, or sales. Keep asking \"So what does this mean for the business?\" until you hit a bottom-line impact.</li>\n          </ul>\n    \n          <p><strong>⚠️ Zero-Mark Trap — Consumer Law vs. Ethical Issues:</strong> Writing about wages, working conditions, or ethical sourcing instead of consumer law will score ZERO — even with perfect application and analysis. The examiner''s report confirms many candidates scored zero for this exact reason.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>❌ Bad Answer (0 marks):</strong><br/>\n          <em>\"One impact of consumer law is that Primark must pay workers a fair wage. Primark sells at cheaper prices than most retailers, so this increases costs.\"</em><br/>\n          This confuses consumer law with employment law. ZERO marks despite having application and analysis.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>✅ Good Answer (3 marks):</strong><br/>\n          <em>\"Consumer law requires goods to be ''not as described'' (U — 1 mark). If Primark Ltd sells clothing or homeware products that do not match their online description (APP — 1 mark to Primark as a low-price retailer), the business could face large volumes of returned goods. Since Primark operates on very tight profit margins, the additional refund costs could significantly reduce overall profitability (AN — 1 mark).\"</em></p>\n    \n          <p><strong>Sentence Starters to use:</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><em>\"Consumer law requires goods to be... (U)\"</em></li>\n            <li><em>\"In the case of [Business]... / Because the text states that... (APP)\"</em></li>\n            <li><em>\"This will lead to... / As a result, the business will... / This reduces... meaning... (AN)\"</em></li>\n          </ul>\n        ", "question": "What are the three steps of the ''Holy Trinity'' structure for a 3-mark analyse question?", "options": ["Application, Evaluation, Reasoning", "Identify, Explain, Conclude", "Understanding, Application, Analysis", "Knowledge, Evaluation, Justification"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The 3-step formula for a 3-mark analyse question is U (Understanding) → APP (Application) → AN (Analysis)."}'::jsonb),
('business:4-4-consumer-law:tips:40981f7e', 'business', 'business:4-4-consumer-law', '4.4 Consumer Law', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Evaluate / Discuss — 7 marks — Four Paragraphs: Two Impacts + a Justified Conclusion", "reading": "\n          <p>A 7-mark question is the most demanding on this topic. You need two separately analysed impacts (with case study application) and a justified evaluative conclusion. Marks: APP (2) + AN (2) + EV (3).</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>The 4-Paragraph Structure:</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><strong>Para 1 — K & U:</strong> Introduce a key requirement of consumer law and explain what this means for a business in general terms.</li>\n            <li><strong>Para 2 — APP & AN (Impact 1):</strong> Apply your first point to the case study using specific details from the text. Analyse the specific financial or operational impact on the business.</li>\n            <li><strong>Para 3 — APP & AN (Impact 2):</strong> Introduce a second, different impact. Apply and analyse in the same way — it must be a different consequence from Para 2.</li>\n            <li><strong>Para 4 — Evaluation (3 marks):</strong>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>Decision (1 mark):</strong> A clear, direct judgement — e.g. \"Consumer law is very important to QUA\" or \"It is more beneficial to comply than not.\"</li>\n                <li><strong>Context (1 mark):</strong> Justify your decision using a specific detail from the case study.</li>\n                <li><strong>Impact/Reasoning (1 mark):</strong> Use a ''depends on'' or ''however'' argument to show nuanced thinking — e.g. \"However, this depends on whether QUA can resolve the quality issues quickly before more negative coverage spreads.\"</li>\n              </ul>\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n    \n          <p><strong>⚠️ Evaluation Warning:</strong> A conclusion that simply repeats your earlier points scores ZERO evaluation marks. Your conclusion must make a NEW, justified judgement that goes beyond what you said in Paragraphs 2 and 3.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>Evaluation Sentence Starters:</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><em>\"Overall, I believe consumer law is [very important / more beneficial / more harmful] to [Business] because...\" (Decision)</em></li>\n            <li><em>\"This is particularly significant because the text states that... (Context)\"</em></li>\n            <li><em>\"However, the full impact will depend on whether... / This matters more because the business... (Reasoning)\"</em></li>\n          </ul>\n        ", "question": "How many marks are allocated to Evaluation (EV) in a 7-mark ''Evaluate/Discuss'' question?", "options": ["2 marks", "4 marks", "7 marks", "3 marks"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The 7 marks split as APP (2) + AN (2) + EV (3), so Evaluation is worth 3 marks."}'::jsonb),
('business:4-4-consumer-law:tips:f427ceea', 'business', 'business:4-4-consumer-law', '4.4 Consumer Law', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Critical Warning — All Question Types — Consumer Law ≠ Ethical Behaviour. Know the Difference.", "reading": "\n          <p>This is the <strong>single most common reason students score zero</strong> on consumer law questions. The examiner''s report explicitly highlighted this as the major failure point across multiple exam sittings.</p>\n    \n          <p><strong>✅ Consumer Law — Legal Requirements (Scoreable):</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li>Goods must be of satisfactory quality ✅</li>\n            <li>Goods must be fit for purpose ✅</li>\n            <li>Goods must be as described ✅</li>\n            <li>Compensation rights for defective or dangerous products ✅</li>\n            <li>30-day return right for faulty goods ✅</li>\n          </ul>\n    \n          <p><strong>❌ NOT Consumer Law — Ethical / Employment Issues (Scores Zero):</strong></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li>Paying workers a fair or living wage ❌</li>\n            <li>Using sustainable or ethical suppliers ❌</li>\n            <li>Reducing environmental impact ❌</li>\n            <li>Treating employees fairly ❌</li>\n            <li>Supporting local communities ❌</li>\n          </ul>\n    \n          <p><strong>📋 Direct from the 2025 Examiner''s Report:</strong><br/>\n          <em>\"Many candidates did not understand consumer law and mixed it up with employment law (many referred to employee rights, fair pay, or working conditions) or ethical considerations. These candidates could not be credited with any marks, despite having application and analysis, due to not specifying any correct understanding.\"</em></p>\n    \n          <p><strong>The Simple Test:</strong> Can you link your point back to \"satisfactory quality,\" \"fit for purpose,\" or \"as described\"? If not, you are likely writing about the wrong topic. Stop and refocus.</p>\n        ", "question": "What is the ''Simple Test'' recommended to check whether a point is genuinely about consumer law?", "options": ["Is the point longer than two written sentences?", "Does it directly reference the Consumer Protection Act?", "Can the point be linked to one of the three requirements?", "Does it mention a named business from the case study?"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The Simple Test checks whether a point can be linked back to one of the three requirements: satisfactory quality, fit for purpose, or as described."}'::jsonb),
